Small-C Revision History

 -- included in version 2.2

 76 Modified _read() in CSYSLIB.C to do console input through _getkey()
    for consistent handling of special key values per the MS-DOS addendum
    to the Small-C Handbook.
 77 Modified fgetc() in FGETC.C to look for an ungotten character and
    return it without cooking it (since it cooked on the original get).
    This fixed an apparent problem in scanf() and fscanf() in which
    they appear to miss input characters.
 78 Revised out_code() and do more optimizing.  Let p-code subscript code[],
    (an array of pointers to output assembly code strings) instead of using
    a monstrous switch statement.
 79 Always compile features that are now considered standard.
 80 Properly calculate swend in main() to use all of the switch table.
 81 Dropped unnecessary variable func1.
 82 Changed if(match(...)); to match(...); statements.
 83 Dropped unnecessary while loop in declloc().
 84 Simplified treatment of argument "dim" in initials().
 85 Dropped outside() because it is redundant with code in compound().
 86 Revised the point at which lval2[] is declared in plnge(), and hier14()
    to greatly reduce the amount of stack space used during expression
    analysis by allocating lval[] arrays only when actually needed. 
 87 Simplified logic in newfunc(), doif(), dodo(), preprocess(), skip(), 
    plnge(), expression(), hier14(), primary(), pstr(), white().  
 88 Modified primary() to add an undeclared function to the symbol table only 
    if the name is not already in the table.  This improves run time by 
    saving a table lookup on most function references.  
 89 Reorganized source code into four files (CC1.C, CC2.C, CC3.C, CC4.C),
    regrouped functions into more logical units, and renamed some functions
    (addmac->dodefine, newfunc->dofunction, rvalue->fetch, pstr->chrcon,
    qstr->string, needtoken->need, col->colon, ol->outline, junk->skip).
 90 Improved output efficiency by deleting cout(), sout(), and xout().
    It now checks for an output error only at the end of a line.
 91 Dropped assignment statements in main() that set globals to zero.
 92 Revised ispunct() to exclude white space from the 'true' condition.
 93 Combined all of the is...() character classification functions into a
    single module of short, fast functions that subscript into an array
    for the answer.  This approach is three times faster.
 94 Per Kiyoshi Akima, eliminated LINK module from library.  Now, trailer()
    declares _MAIN to be external if main() is declared in the module being 
    compiled; this forces CSYSLIB to load when linking.  By not declaring it 
    external in other modules, a "multiply defined" error is eliminated when 
    compiling CSYSLIB which contains _MAIN.  However, since .OBJ modules
    which were compiled with earlier versions of Small-C contain references to 
    __LINK, it is declared as a dummy entry point in CALL.ASM to avoid 
    "unresolved reference" errors at link time.
 95 Per Kiyoshi Akima, installed additional code optimizing.
 96 Dropped setops() in favor of initializing the op[] and op2[] arrays.
    This can be done since these arrays now contain p-codes rather than
    function addresses.
 97 Yet another rewrite of the the optimizer.  It's now much smaller, each 
    optimization is cheaper, the logic is clearer and more bullet proof.
    And, yet more optimizations.  EXE sizes are down by 10% and execution times
    are down by as much as 25%.
 98 Renamed CC.DEF to CC.H and CLIB.DEF to CLIB.H.
 99 Corrected unlink() to return ERR on failure instead of EOF.
100 Revision 76 slowed down the reading of files considerably by introducing
    an additional call to iscons() for every character read.  It was discovered
    that the DOS interrupt in this function is very very slow.  So, iscons()
    was revised to call DOS only the first time for a file, and then test
    the rememberred answer thereafter.  This required changes to CSYSLIB.C
    also.  The effect was a DOUBLING OF I/O SPEED DURING READS, compared to
    revision level 75 -- BEFORE the slowdown was introduced.  This shows that
    the existing calls to iscons() in fgetc() and fgets() have been a major
    bottleneck all along.
101 Added the "unsigned" integer and character data types.  These result in
    unsigned <, <=, >, >=, *, /, % operations and yield unsigned results.
102 Revised the handling of numeric constants to recognize values from
    32768 to 65535 as unsigned.  These, likewise, produce unsigned operations
    and yield unsigned results.
103 Cleaned up the handling of non-definitional function declarations.  The 
    syntax (*func)(), which specifies a pointer to a function, is now accepted 
    only for function arguments.  Previously, it was accepted at the global and 
    local levels, but not interpreted as a pointer.
104 Reject instances of declarations, such as *func(), which have multiple
    modifiers.  Previously, the right most modifier prevailed.  But it is 
    better to reject something than to interpret in differently than it is
    written.
105 Accept "void" before function header as comment.
106 Corrected an error in the expression analyzer which causes pointer offsets
    to be lost when subscripting is applied; e.g., (ptr+5)[x] would lose the
    offset 5.
107 Revised the implementation of the sizeof() operator so it works correctly.
    Although undocumented, this was in the original MS-DOS compiler.
108 Always pass an argument count to functions, even if NOCCARGC is defined.
    This is not very costly on 8086 family CPUs and it eliminates a lot of
    headaches when you call printf() but forget that NOCCARGC is defined.
109 Small-C programs now abort with a return code of 1 for memory overflows
    and 2 for operator interruptions (control-C).
110 Revised strlen() to use the 8086 "REPNE SCASB" prefix/instruction for 
    the fastest possible operation.  Sped it up over 500%.
111 Any redirection of stdout overrides the assumed output of the compiler,
    not just redirections to disk files.
112 Revised hier2() (now called level2()), which processes the ?: operator,
    so that it groups properly from right to left and yields meaningful
    attributes for further expression analysis.  This involved imposing
    consistency restrictions on the second and third expressions.
113 Revised dogoto(), dolabel(), and addlabel() to catch duplicate label
    definitions.
114 Revised outname() to write names to the output file without forcing them to 
    uppercase.  Except for this function, the compiler was already case 
    sensitive.  Also recompiled and assembled the library with lowercase names.
115 Modified the p-code translation strings containing "CALL xxx", where xxx
    is a CALL module entry point, so that xxx is in lower case.  This 
    eliminates errors when case sensitivity is specified to the assembler and
    the linker.
116 Made minor revisions to allow command-line switches to be introduced by
    slashes (/) as well as hyphens (-).  This is consistant with the Small
    Assembler which accommodates slashes for consistency with the PC/MS-DOS
    linker which it employs.
117 Revised optimization cases 31 thru 33 to prevent generating corrupt code 
    for statements like ++x[4]; where x[] is local.  Previously this statement 
    would update the wrong memory location.  Deleted cases 31 and 32, and 
    changed case 33 to do less optimizing.  Renumbered cases 33 thru 49 as
    31 thru 47.  
118 Permit C99 style one-line comments, replaced Quote[] with inline string
    literal. Consolidated type recognition in dofunction() and move function
    argument parsing to its own function.
119 Permit C90 style argument lists, where types are inline with the 
    variable names. Adds support for 'static' global variables. Longer
    variable names permitted.

 -- included in version 2.3

120 Support added for structs.
121 Support added for multi-dimensional arrays of ints, chars, structs.
    Multi-dimensional arrays can be initialized (not structs, though).
    Function parameters accept int b[][C] syntax for passing multi-dimensional
    arrays. The first dimension is omitted (the pointer), while remaining
    dimensions provide stride information for subscript computation.
    Added BYTE PTR qualifier to GETb1m, GETb1mu, and PUTbm1 code templates
    to prevent assembler errors when peephole-optimized byte accesses
    reference word-declared labels.
    Added PUSH2 to gen() csp tracking.
122 New peephole optimizations:
    (1) Eliminate LNEG before conditional jump (seq48-49): When !expr appears
    in a boolean context, the compiler emits CALL __lneg followed by a
    conditional jump. The CALL is unnecessary — flipping the jump sense from
    NE10f to EQ10f (or vice versa) produces identical behavior. Saves 3 bytes.
    (2) Inline comparison + conditional jump (seq50-59): When comparisons like
    a == b appear in boolean context, the compiler emits a CALL to a library
    routine (__eq, __ne, __lt, etc.) that returns 0/1 in AX, followed by a
    test-and-jump. This two-step sequence is replaced with a single inline
    CMP AX,BX / Jcc $+5 / JMP _label using the condition codes from CALL.ASM.
    Ten new p-codes (EQf through GEuf) cover all comparisons. Saves 3 bytes.
    (3) Direct stack stores (seq60-61): Every assignment to a local variable
    generates LEA BX,n[BP] / MOV [BX],AX. When BX is not needed afterward, this
    collapses to MOV n[BP],AX. Two new p-codes (PUTws1 for words, PUTbs1 for
    bytes) mirror existing load-path optimization in seq42. Saves 2 bytes.
    (4) Constant shift by 1 (seq62-63): The 8086 can shift by 1 or by CL. The
    compiler always uses the CL path: MOV CX,AX / MOV AX,BX / SAL AX,CL. When
    the shift amount is constant 1, this is replaced with MOV AX,BX / SHL AX,1.
    Two p-codes (ASL1_1 and ASR1_1) do left and right shifts. Saves 2 bytes.
123 Fix commutes bug in cc4, repairing seq27. See correct pattern in isfree().
    Discovered by Fred J. Scipione (@FredJScipione on GitHub).
124 Support for pointer arrays and initialization: char* varname[] = { ... }
    Do not allow use of reserved keywords list. Note that this compiler
    continues to support a (growing) amount of the C language; just because a
    keyword is reserved does not mean the feature associated with that keyword
    has been implemented.
125 Fixed overflow bug in CC1.C (incorrectly calculated slast and swend).
126 Added 32-bit 'long' and 'unsigned long' integer types. Supports
    declarations, initialization, arithmetic (+, -, *, /, %, shifts,
    bitwise), comparisons, pointer-to-long arithmetic, multi-dimensional
    long arrays, long struct members, long function parameters and return
    values, explicit casts between long and narrower types, and switch on
    long expressions. printf/scanf recognize %ld, %lu, and %lx. Numeric
    literals accept L, U, UL suffixes. C90 type promotion rules apply.
    Long values occupy 4 bytes. It is intended that local long variables
    are 2-byte aligned on the stack.
127 Fixed // comment handler in preprocess() (CC2.C) to not read past end of
    buffer into the parent file, which dropped the line after a #include when
    the included file had no trailing newline. Added input line/filename
    tracking (lineno, inclno, infn[], inclfn[]) so error() prefixes each
    message with "filename(lineno)". Added multi-platform line-ending support:
    preprocess() stops on CR or LF; doinclude() strips CR from filenames;
    fgetc() (FGETC.C) now treats standalone LF as a line terminator and
    consumes the LF in a CRLF pair.
128 Added peephole optimizations seq64-73 (CC4.C) for the EQ10f (jump-if-true)
    variants of the comparison-plus-conditional-jump sequences introduced in
    revision 122. seq50-59 already handled COMPxx followed by NE10f, covering
    comparisons used directly in boolean context. When a comparison is negated
    with !, seq48 converts LNEG1,NE10f to EQ10f, but the resulting
    COMPxx,EQ10f pair was not caught, causing the comparison library call and
    OR AX,AX test to remain in the output. seq64-73 handle all ten comparisons
    (signed and unsigned) paired with EQ10f by replacing them with a single
    inline CMP AX,BX / Jcc $+5 / JMP using the inverted condition code.
    Eliminates one CALL and one OR AX,AX (3 bytes each site) from every
    negated comparison in boolean context. Raised HIGH_SEQ from 63 to 73.
129 Added static local variables. The 'static' keyword on a local declaration
    allocates storage in the DATA segment (zero-initialised by default) rather
    than on the stack, giving the variable permanent lifetime across calls, but
    is invisible outside the enclosing function, as each static local gets a
    unique assembly label _L<N> (where N is the existing label counter) stored
    in the global symbol table. The local symbol table entry for scoping holds
    the short user-supplied name, with its OFFSET field pointing to the
    global entry. primary() detects CLASS==STATIC and redirects through that
    pointer to obtain the correct IDENT, TYPE, and NDIM fields and emit a
    POINT1m/GETw1m reference rather than a stack-relative access.
    emitStatLoc() handles constant-only initializers for scalars, arrays, and
    struct aggregates at declaration time.
130 Added a warning() function (suppressible with new -w flag); if any warnings
    are output, a summary prints at end of compilation.
    Fixed a bug in the & operator (cc3.c) where taking the address of a long
    variable left TYP_OBJ set, causing isLongVal() to emit PUSHd1 (two words:
    PUSH DX + PUSH AX) for the resulting pointer instead of PUSH1 (one word).
    This broke any pattern of the form btell(fd, &offset) where offset is a
    long. Fixed in both the local-variable path (added is[TYP_OBJ] = 0) and
    the global-variable path (removed the erroneous is[TYP_OBJ] = ptr[TYPE]).
    Added is[TYP_VAL] to record type after explicit cast; IsUnsigned() now
    checks is[TYP_VAL] & IS_UNSIGNED. Fixes fixing chained casts such as
    (unsigned long)(uint)x. applycast() stores cast type in TYP_VAL and issues
    a compile-time warning when widening a signed value to unsigned long.
    Moved reserved-keyword checking out of symname() into all individual
    declaration sites (globals, function args, local vars, struct names) so name
    lookup is never suppressed by the check.
    Replaced InitPtrArray() limit of 50 elements with MAXARRAYDIM define (200).
    Converted the code[] p-code table in cc4.c from a runtime-populated int
    array (setcodes()) to a static char* array with inline initializers, saving
    3000 bytes of compiled EXE!
131 Added C90 enum support. Enumerators are named constants backed by int.
132 Added C90 type qualifiers: const, signed, short, volatile, and register.
    const is enforced at compile time: assigning to or incrementing a const
    variable is a compile error. CONST_FLAG (0x80) is packed into the high bit
    of the CLASS byte in the symbol table. signed is accepted as an explicit
    modifier (int is already signed). short maps to int/unsigned int, which
    are 16-bit. volatile and register are silently accepted but have no effect
    because the 8086 has no free GPRs for register allocation, and all
    variables round-trip through memory in Small-C model.
    Fixed genStore() and genStoreZero() for 32-bit (long) local initializers:
    both previously stored the low word twice instead of using PUTdp1 to
    write DX:AX as a dword.
    Fixed down2() to call widen_primary() instead of hard-coding WIDENs when
    widening a 16-bit left operand for a mixed-width binary operation, so
    unsigned short values are zero-extended rather than sign-extended.
    Fixed applycast() constant-folding to sign-extend 8-bit results for signed
    char targets (was masking to 8 bits without extending).
133 Comprehensive use of C90 arg lists throughout Small-C, SmallLib, and Ylink.
134 Add adjacent string concatenation.
135 Size optimization: two new p-codes change ADD SP,{1,2} to POP CX,{1,2}.
136 Added void pointer support. void* is accepted as a type; pointer arithmetic
    and dereferencing behave as for char*.
137 Added a second optimization pass: a per-function buffer accumulates all
    CODE-segment p-codes for a function. At the end of each function, a
    two-pass optimizer (flushfunc) calculates label byte offsets, then
    replaces any long branch triple (OR/CMP + Jcc $+5 + JMP near, 7 bytes)
    with a short conditional jump (OR/CMP + Jcc label, 4 bytes) wherever the
    target is within +-127 bytes. Nineteen new short-branch p-codes (177-195)
    cover all signed, unsigned, and zero-test comparisons. Stack-overflow risk
    from large static arrays was eliminated by heap-allocating the function
    buffer. Inline #asm blocks appear are flushed before emitting assembly.
138 Added C90 function prototype support. extern declarations and forward
    declarations with typed parameter lists (including f(void) and f(...)) are
    parsed and stored under a new PROTOEXT storage class. Parameter types are
    recorded in a new paramTypes[] buffer (indexed via a repurposed
    FNPARAMPTR/SIZE field).
    Non-variadic prototyped functions no longer receive an ARGCNTn argument
    count in CL at call sites; variadic and unknown functions still get it.
    Added optional WARN_IMPLICIT and WARN_ARGCOUNT diagnostic flags.
    Added function prototypes to cc.h and stdio.h.
    Renamed internal skip() to skipToNextToken() to avoid conflict with the
    stdlib skip() now declared in stdio.h.

 -- included in version 2.4

139 Flipped calling convention to right-to-left (cdecl): arguments are now
    pushed right-to-left so the first parameter always lands at [BP+4], the
    second at [BP+6], etc.
    callfunc() rewritten to two-pass scheme: first pass evaluates each argument
    left-to-right into a scratch buffer (argbuf); second pass replays those
    p-codes in reverse order, appending each with PUSH. Buffer cursor is saved/
    restored per call nesting level.
    doArgsTyped(): offsets now sequential from [BP+4], reversal loop removed.
    ARGCNTn p-code 5 retired, and its place in the P-Code array replaced with
    JMPs, which used to be 174. We continue to use nargcnt for WARN_ARGCOUNT
    prototype checks.
    Indirect call bug fix: the pointer is saved into a temp stack slot before
    argument evaluation and reloaded afterward.
    Struct assignment push order corrected to match R-to-L layout.
    Four peephole optimizations that folded PUSH/POP pairs disabled because
    they misfire when p-codes are replayed from argbuf.
    Defines WARN_IMPLICIT, WARN_ARGCOUNT are guarded by ENABLE_WARNINGS.
    SmallLib: _ccargc removed (relied on ARGCNTn / CL register handoff).
    printf, fprintf, scanf, fscanf rewritten to take explicit fmt parameter
    and walk arg stack upward from [BP+4]. Stack-frame offsets in assembly
    routines changed to right-to-left. udiv3216 updated for same reason.
140 Changed optimization table to permit more detailed optimization rules.
    Refactored three switch statements in cc3.c into data-driven lookup tables
    (toLongTab, reverseTab, cmpOpTab) plus a generic tableFind() helper, and
    added reverseOp() to map a comparison operator to its operand-swapped
    counterpart (LT<->GT, LE<->GE, etc.). Used reverseOp() in down2() to
    enable two new code-generation shortcuts: (1) when a non-commutative
    operator has a constant RHS, try reversing rather than emitting MOVE21
    followed by GETw1n; (2) when a word-sized variable was just loaded as the
    RHS, retract the load, reverse the operator, and emit GETw2m/GETw2s
    directly so that the existing CMP-Memory/Stack peephole rules can fire.
141 Add unions, which are like structs, except all of their members start
    at base address 0 for a union struct. Because they are like structs,
    I reused most of the struct code.
142 Optimization: don't emit or ax, ax where not necessary.
143 Add typedef
144 Added SHORT qualifier to all short-branch p-codes. Previously these
    emitted bare conditional jumps (e.g. "JNE _<n>") which the assembler
    assembles as near jumps; now they are forced to correct 2-byte encoding.
    Frame Pointer Omission (FPO) optimization. BP can be dropped when it is
    never read inside a function. A new pass in flushfunc() scans the function
    p-code buffer for any BP-relative p-code; if none is found AND the function
    contains no inline #asm block, ENTER is replaced with NOP_ (emits nothing)
    and every RETURN with RETNOFP, which emits a one-byte RET. Functions with
    #asm blocks are unconditionally excluded because inline assembly is flushed
    directly to the output file and may reference BP outside the p-code view.
    Epilogue Consolidation optimization.  When a function has two or more RETURN
    p-codes and frame-pointer omission did not apply, all RETURN p-codes except
    the last are replaced with JMPm to a shared epilogue label, and the last
    RETURN slot is repurposed as that label followed by a single RETURN.
    Each eliminated duplicate epilogue saves 2 bytes (5-byte JMP to  2-byte JMP
    short, vs. the 4-byte POP BP / RET it replaces). Functions where FP was
    omitted are not eligible, as we can just RETNOFP (1 byte).
145 Many fixes, add add sprintf to SmallLib's C library.
    Three C90 fixes for pointer cast expressions (type *):
    Fix A (cc3.c level13): unary * now checks is[TYP_ADR] before SYMTAB_ADR
    when setting TYP_OBJ, so *(unsigned char *)voidptr does not trigger the
    "cannot dereference void pointer" error and *(T *)p respects the cast type.
    Fix B (cc3.c fetch): indirect byte load uses is[TYP_OBJ] & IS_UNSIGNED
    instead of ptr[TYPE] & IS_UNSIGNED, so (unsigned char *) casts generate
    GETb1pu (zero-extend) rather than GETb1p (sign-extend).
    Fix C (cc3.c level14): subscript element-scale uses a local elemType =
    is[TYP_ADR] ? is[TYP_ADR] : ptr[TYPE], so ((char *)intptr)[n] scales the
    index by 1 byte, not 2.
    Fix D (cc1.c doArgsTyped): void* is now a valid function parameter type.
    Previously, seeing TYPE_VOID as the first parameter triggered the f(void)
    zero-parameter path before the loop had a chance to match '*'. Now a peek
    at ch after blanks() distinguishes 'void)' (zero params) from 'void *'
    (pointer-to-void param). All combinations (void* alone, void* + typed
    params, multiple void* params) now compile correctly.
    Fix E (cc4.c flushfunc FPO pass): the Frame Pointer Omission pass now
    correctly blocks omission when RETURN.value != 0, i.e. when the callee
    needs MOV SP,BP to restore the stack pointer before RET. Previously, a
    local variable only used in sizeof() would emit ADDSP(-N) but no
    BP-relative p-code; the FPO pass saw no BP use and eliminated ENTER/RETURN,
    leaving ADD SP,-N with no matching restore, corrupting the return address.
    RETURN.value is the canonical "needs frame restoration" signal and is
    already computed by the time flushfunc() runs.
146 Local struct initialization with = { ... } passes all tests.
    Fixed a bug in initLocStrMem() and initLocUnion() where the 4-instruction
    manual long-store sequence (PUTwp1 / ADD2n / GETw1n / PUTwp1) clobbered
    AX with zero before storing the high word, corrupting any long value whose
    upper 16 bits were non-zero. Replaced with genStore() / PUTdp1.
147 Significant reorganization and code optimization. Renamed functions from
    PascalCase to camelCase (IsMatch->isMatch, etc.) for naming consistency.
    Removed ENABLE_ENUMS and ENABLE_TYPEDEF compile-time guards; both features
    are now always compiled. Adjusted buffer sizes: NUMGLBS 380->500,
    LITABSZ 5000->4200, FNPARAMTS_SZ 768->1024; added FL_LABMAX (256) for the
    short-branch label table. Folded small internal helpers (keepch, ifline,
    noiferr) into their sole callers to reduce call overhead.
    Pre-processor code is now in ccpre.c.
